WEBVTT

00:00.016 --> 00:00.760
(grunting)

00:00.859 --> 00:03.460
<i>Narrator: Previously,
on AMC's Hell On Wheels.</i>

00:03.477 --> 00:05.679
You can't quit now, I won't allow it.

00:05.780 --> 00:07.019
(bottle breaks)

00:07.119 --> 00:11.184
You realize what I could accomplish among
our workers on the Central Pacific?

00:11.285 --> 00:12.752
They tell me you quit the U.P.

00:12.853 --> 00:13.929
Is that true?

00:14.129 --> 00:16.189
You'd have a record of where they
went and that's all I'm askin' for.

00:16.290 --> 00:18.857
There is a better way to find your family.

00:18.959 --> 00:23.296
If you work for me all of my
resources will be at your disposal.

00:23.397 --> 00:25.798
Sherman Peak is behind me, stop.

00:25.899 --> 00:29.668
I am coming for you, stop.

00:31.000 --> 00:37.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:43.583 --> 00:44.850
(SIGHS)

00:53.126 --> 00:54.459
NAOMI: Cullen!

01:02.735 --> 01:05.102
There he is. Go get him, William.

01:20.719 --> 01:22.485
Come on.

01:22.519 --> 01:24.354
Come here. (GRUNTS)

01:25.223 --> 01:27.991
Ah, you got me. (GROWLS)

01:30.628 --> 01:32.129
NAOMI: Cullen!

01:33.697 --> 01:35.698
It's time to come in for supper.

01:37.801 --> 01:40.002
Mama made us fried chicken and pie.

01:40.036 --> 01:42.772
Fried chicken and pie? Oh!
That sounds good!

01:42.806 --> 01:44.407
I think I'm gonna have a
piece of pie about that big.

01:44.441 --> 01:45.975
You want one like that? Yeah?

01:46.510 --> 01:48.144
- Okay, I'll be up real soon.
- Okay.

01:48.178 --> 01:49.712
Go see Mama. All right.

01:52.149 --> 01:53.249
(CHUCKLES)

01:58.221 --> 01:59.454
(SIGHS)

02:13.269 --> 02:15.337
(WIND HOWLING)

02:30.452 --> 02:32.821
Dear God, what I'd give for a campfire,

02:32.855 --> 02:35.690
a bowl of stew, and a nice
warm spot to put my...

02:35.724 --> 02:37.091
Shut the hell up, Shorty.

02:38.861 --> 02:40.228
(GRUNTS)

03:06.855 --> 03:08.922
(PANTING)

03:11.826 --> 03:13.160
Holy shit.

03:14.562 --> 03:16.696
Is that what I think it is?

03:18.366 --> 03:19.999
I believe it is.

03:21.068 --> 03:22.635
(CHUCKLES)

03:23.537 --> 03:25.605
You did it, you bastard.

03:26.774 --> 03:28.775
Break out the whiskey, ya gypsies,

03:28.809 --> 03:31.611
Bohannon's found the mother
whoring route to Utah.

03:31.645 --> 03:33.179
(LAUGHS)

04:21.567 --> 04:25.011
<font color="#ff0000">Sync and corrections by btsix
www.addic7ed.com</font>

04:27.599 --> 04:29.799
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

04:51.889 --> 04:53.923
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

05:32.494 --> 05:34.795
Bohannon, you ugly piece of work.

05:35.397 --> 05:37.832
'Bout time you showed
that mug back in Truckee.

05:38.133 --> 05:39.617
I'm touched you missed me, Jim.

05:40.035 --> 05:41.201
Saved you plenty of granite.

05:41.570 --> 05:43.070
Not too much, I hope.

05:43.104 --> 05:44.622
Couple of miles, give or take.

05:45.340 --> 05:48.142
- It's been a month.
- Inches a day, Bohannon.

05:48.176 --> 05:49.279
Works for the wife.

05:49.445 --> 05:52.447
Come around tonight for supper
with me and Mrs. Strobridge.

05:52.749 --> 05:53.916
You'll like her.

05:58.588 --> 06:00.155
(GROANS) Ah.

06:08.564 --> 06:10.799
Mr. Bohannon!

06:11.200 --> 06:14.002
You have the visage of
a great explorer, sir,

06:14.036 --> 06:16.104
returned from this wild
continent's dark places.

06:16.138 --> 06:18.440
I hope to light the way for civilization.

06:18.474 --> 06:19.974
Tell me you've found the route to Ogden.

06:20.642 --> 06:23.111
Straight through the coal
fields of Weber Canyon.

06:25.214 --> 06:27.313
Straight down the throat
of the Union Pacific.

06:27.316 --> 06:29.550
Now, we go through the
mountains here, and here,

06:30.019 --> 06:32.686
then we're into the Nevada
desert and all the way to Utah.

06:32.721 --> 06:34.622
Shaves 100 miles off our previous route.

06:34.656 --> 06:36.124
If we don't wither in the desert.

06:36.158 --> 06:38.191
We've got 15,000 workers, Bohannon,

06:38.226 --> 06:40.961
Irish and Chinamen combined,
plus livestock.

06:40.995 --> 06:44.331
Not to mention Mrs. Strobridge,
our kids, their dogs.

06:44.365 --> 06:45.800
Thirsty bastards, all.

06:45.834 --> 06:47.802
No, the creeks are marked. (SIGHS)

06:47.836 --> 06:50.704
We build dams here, and
here for tank ponds.

06:50.739 --> 06:52.606
- Trout in them ponds?
- We can stock them.

06:52.641 --> 06:53.706
The rest we take from the Sierras.

06:53.741 --> 06:55.375
Meltage from the snowpack this spring.

06:55.410 --> 06:57.377
Build tanks, ship 'em out on the flatbeds.

06:57.412 --> 06:59.411
The snowpack idea ain't bad.

06:59.414 --> 07:01.514
I been known to come through on occasion.

07:04.018 --> 07:06.987
Congratulations, gentlemen. We might
just have a shot at winning this race.

07:07.322 --> 07:08.956
Oh, uh,

07:08.990 --> 07:11.658
Chang has fresh Chinamen
out by his rice hut.

07:14.394 --> 07:16.328
Any of them telegrams for me?

07:21.401 --> 07:23.001
It's only been a month.

07:24.003 --> 07:25.837
No luck finding your wife and child?

07:27.773 --> 07:30.975
Well, we have ongoing business
with the Mormons, Mr. Bohannon.

07:31.677 --> 07:33.878
I'm sure Brigham Young will
answer our inquiry eventually.

07:36.015 --> 07:38.216
Yeah. I'll see to Chang.

07:44.289 --> 07:46.357
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

07:53.044 --> 07:55.980
_

07:56.067 --> 08:02.579
_

08:03.167 --> 08:05.981
_

08:06.667 --> 08:07.717
_

08:08.246 --> 08:09.246
Boss man.

08:10.982 --> 08:12.082
Mr. Bohannon,

08:12.117 --> 08:15.018
an honor to finally serve
you in my humble rice shop.

08:16.608 --> 08:18.746
What can I get for you?
Something to eat? Tea?

08:19.011 --> 08:20.611
Just them workers right there.

08:22.915 --> 08:26.417
Oh, in China, it's an offense to refuse
a host's offer of food or drink.

08:28.587 --> 08:30.320
But this isn't China, thank God.

08:31.957 --> 08:33.789
I fought for the Taiping Kingdom.

08:34.892 --> 08:39.328
Yeah, your leader thought he
was a brother of Jesus Christ,

08:39.364 --> 08:40.864
something like that.

08:40.898 --> 08:43.232
But then he had y'all hanging
human meat in the marketplace.

08:43.268 --> 08:46.303
Well, atrocities were
committed on both sides.

08:47.072 --> 08:49.072
As they were in America's Civil War.

08:49.907 --> 08:52.642
Andersonville Prison comes to mind.

08:53.143 --> 08:56.379
Tragic, but that's what
happens in war, isn't it?

08:58.916 --> 09:02.285
Yeah. That should be enough
pay for about 50 workers.

09:03.087 --> 09:06.655
As you know, I provide so much more
than tunnel fodder for my friends.

09:06.690 --> 09:08.724
Spirits, opium, women.

09:09.593 --> 09:11.394
What's your pleasure?

09:12.329 --> 09:16.165
Workers will be fine. Let's get these
men to the work site, Mr. Tao.

09:18.302 --> 09:19.635
(SPEAKING CANTONESE)

10:17.869 --> 10:19.637
Lot of new recruits.

10:20.439 --> 10:22.440
These men got a railroad
where they're from?

10:22.975 --> 10:25.275
Guangdong province is very poor.

10:26.277 --> 10:28.979
Many villages devastated by rebels.

10:30.415 --> 10:31.884
Men like Chang.

10:32.717 --> 10:35.453
Here we are all guests of Gold Mountain.

10:37.088 --> 10:38.622
Chang bad man.

10:38.657 --> 10:39.957
(SPEAKING CANTONESE)

10:43.194 --> 10:45.329
Please forgive my son, Mr. Bohannon.

10:45.363 --> 10:49.466
He is young, his manners are
bad, and his English is worse.

10:49.500 --> 10:50.733
Maybe.

10:52.036 --> 10:54.171
But I'm inclined to agree with him.

11:09.587 --> 11:11.053
God damn it, John!

11:11.088 --> 11:14.923
Get your rice-eating asses back
down there and repack that powder!

11:18.428 --> 11:20.562
Jesus, Bohannon.

11:20.597 --> 11:23.699
Leave the Johns to that Hell's
mouth and get back to your desk.

11:23.733 --> 11:26.101
You're a stakeholder, for God's sake.

11:26.236 --> 11:28.204
Never have learned how to sit
behind a desk, Mr. Strobridge.

11:28.238 --> 11:31.773
If I was you, I'd figure it out. It's
tight as a Chinese trap down there

11:31.808 --> 11:34.376
and smells about as good
as a syphilitic whore.

11:34.410 --> 11:36.044
Least it ain't downwind of you.

11:36.078 --> 11:37.679
You're liable to lose a limb.

11:39.516 --> 11:41.082
Keep an eye out for me, Jim.

11:43.820 --> 11:44.820
(GRUNTS)

11:46.955 --> 11:49.491
(MEN SPEAKING CANTONESE INDISTINCTLY)

12:01.504 --> 12:03.270
Y'all started the horizontal blasting?

12:03.304 --> 12:04.839
TAO: Yes, boss man.

12:13.615 --> 12:15.449
- (SCREAMS)
- (SPEAKING CANTONESE)

12:15.884 --> 12:16.984
(WHIMPERING)

12:27.529 --> 12:28.529
You any good with that thing?

12:34.035 --> 12:35.069
Come on.

12:37.605 --> 12:38.905
(EXHALES)

12:39.173 --> 12:40.640
(YELLING)

12:54.088 --> 12:55.521
Ah, that should be good.

12:56.190 --> 12:58.289
- Black powder?
- (SPEAKS CANTONESE)

12:58.520 --> 13:03.096
(MAN SPEAKS CANTONESE)

13:11.404 --> 13:13.538
- Clear out!
- Yes, sir.

13:14.178 --> 13:16.280
(SPEAKING CANTONESE)

13:32.091 --> 13:35.013
You too. I got this. Go.

13:35.861 --> 13:38.530
Boss man stay, I stay.

14:17.035 --> 14:18.401
Easy! Easy!

14:19.804 --> 14:20.937
(YELLING)

14:30.948 --> 14:32.081
Go!

14:34.785 --> 14:37.387
Get them out of there! Come on!

15:01.277 --> 15:02.644
(GRUNTS)

15:16.259 --> 15:18.026
(GROANING)

15:32.753 --> 15:36.809
Hey. Keep it covered.
Keep it cool, all right?

15:36.812 --> 15:37.946
Thank you, boss man.

15:38.679 --> 15:40.180
Name's Bohannon.

15:41.682 --> 15:42.816
Fong.

15:43.356 --> 15:45.057
Thank you, Fong.

15:45.292 --> 15:46.358
Hey.

15:53.900 --> 15:55.501
Chang. He steal.

15:55.968 --> 15:58.270
Chang steal Chinese gold eagle.

15:58.305 --> 16:00.138
(STUTTERS) Pay roll.

16:01.153 --> 16:04.255
Chang take half. Chinese have family. Debt.

16:04.756 --> 16:06.123
Need gold eagle.

16:09.962 --> 16:11.062
I'll tend to my son.

16:12.664 --> 16:15.266
(SPEAKING CANTONESE)

16:17.736 --> 16:19.603
(FONG SIGHS AND WHIMPERS)

16:21.539 --> 16:23.240
(HORSE WHINNYING)

16:29.647 --> 16:31.582
Welcome, what's your pleasure?

16:32.616 --> 16:34.650
I need to have a word with your boss.

16:35.853 --> 16:39.289
Mr. Bohannon, you've reconsidered my offer.

16:40.157 --> 16:41.824
Uh, no.

16:42.559 --> 16:45.428
I come to see you distribute
the Chinese payroll square.

16:50.300 --> 16:53.736
Payroll distribution has
continued without incident.

16:54.204 --> 16:56.372
You're skimming the wages. That stops now.

17:01.912 --> 17:03.846
This is very unusual,

17:05.580 --> 17:08.150
a white man coming into my establishment

17:08.184 --> 17:11.387
to lecture me on how I conduct my business.

17:11.820 --> 17:13.222
The railroad is my business, Mr. Chang,

17:13.256 --> 17:14.790
and all the workers on it.

17:15.791 --> 17:19.528
Well, the Chinese workers are contracted
through my company, Mr. Bohannon,

17:19.561 --> 17:21.496
for a negotiated price.

17:22.164 --> 17:26.334
How we then compensate those
workers is Chinese business.

17:35.144 --> 17:37.879
You sell your dope, pimp your whores.

17:39.014 --> 17:41.149
If you don't want me back in here regular,

17:41.183 --> 17:43.084
pay the workers what they're owed.

17:44.987 --> 17:47.088
Give my regards to Mr. Tao.

17:54.163 --> 17:58.632
He's a pirate, whelped
aboard a British opium ship

17:58.667 --> 18:01.602
commandeered in South China sea.

18:01.636 --> 18:04.171
Chang's father was a Manchurian prince

18:04.205 --> 18:08.909
who turned to piracy after a
failed plot to murder his brother.

18:08.944 --> 18:11.445
But it was his mother,

18:11.479 --> 18:14.948
a Polynesian beauty pillaged
from her tribe of cannibals,

18:14.983 --> 18:19.252
that gave him his taste for human flesh.

18:19.620 --> 18:21.855
Stop it, James! They'll never sleep!

18:21.889 --> 18:24.557
- (CHUCKLES)
- That's not real.

18:25.159 --> 18:26.360
Do you believe that's real?

18:27.561 --> 18:29.696
Uh, it's nothing your daddy can't handle.

18:30.764 --> 18:34.617
Chang is, uh, stealing from
his own people, though.

18:34.935 --> 18:37.236
That's between him and his Chinese.

18:37.270 --> 18:40.172
- Doesn't concern us.
- Concerns the workers.

18:41.241 --> 18:44.210
Chang provides our workforce, Mr. Bohannon.

18:44.244 --> 18:47.413
And he takes a little from them
off the top, that's his business.

18:48.148 --> 18:50.349
Them Chinese struck last year over wages.

18:50.384 --> 18:52.451
Now they got Chang taking a piece.

18:53.420 --> 18:55.021
Only a matter of time
till they strike again.

18:55.288 --> 18:56.755
Chang keeps them in line.

18:59.559 --> 19:02.761
Sooner or later, a beat dog bites.

19:09.035 --> 19:10.536
PHINEAS YOUNG: Heavenly Father.

19:13.540 --> 19:15.040
Thank you.

19:17.309 --> 19:18.910
Thank you for...

19:26.785 --> 19:28.753
I'm sorry, brothers, I
know not what to say.

19:29.155 --> 19:33.791
Heavenly Father, bless this loathsome gruel

19:35.060 --> 19:36.961
we have set before us.

19:38.263 --> 19:41.832
Thank thee for this time
with our beloved companions,

19:42.901 --> 19:45.937
Hunger, Want and Desolation.

19:47.172 --> 19:51.375
Bless this frigid, lonesome desert,

19:51.409 --> 19:55.446
this emptiness which threatens
to freeze our hearts.

19:56.548 --> 19:59.649
For though we are alone

19:59.684 --> 20:02.119
and surrounded by wolves,

20:03.688 --> 20:05.989
we know we are not forsaken...

20:08.993 --> 20:10.594
For our faith sustains us.

20:10.628 --> 20:12.796
In the name of Jesus Christ.

20:13.464 --> 20:16.666
And our prophet, my father,
Brigham Young in Zion.

20:17.001 --> 20:19.368
- Amen.
- ALL: Amen.

20:22.506 --> 20:23.606
Yeah.

20:30.947 --> 20:32.915
Thank you, brother Thor.

20:33.117 --> 20:36.719
We must not lose faith, brother Phineas.

20:40.556 --> 20:43.558
Sometimes I fear it is my
father who has lost faith.

20:44.728 --> 20:45.928
In me.

20:48.264 --> 20:49.965
I believe in you, brother.

20:52.969 --> 20:54.637
Hmm. Yeah.

20:56.072 --> 20:57.606
(SLURPS) Mmm.

21:08.117 --> 21:10.852
This is from my hen, Peep.

21:13.588 --> 21:14.689
Hmm.

21:15.124 --> 21:16.790
Make sure to thank her for me, all right?

21:17.159 --> 21:18.425
I will.

21:20.094 --> 21:24.365
My daddy says we're to be nice to you
on account of you're real lonely.

21:38.512 --> 21:40.413
From Brigham Young. (SIGHS)

21:40.447 --> 21:42.282
I thought it should wait 'til after supper.

21:43.785 --> 21:46.352
They've been cast out of
all Mormon settlements.

21:57.964 --> 22:01.401
- They banished my family.
- Hell of a thing.

22:05.839 --> 22:07.372
They could be anywhere.

22:47.028 --> 22:48.661
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

22:53.334 --> 22:54.701
(COCKS GUN)

23:06.614 --> 23:08.147
STROBRIDGE: Don't shoot.

23:08.449 --> 23:10.417
I just want to play cards.

23:18.858 --> 23:22.194
My kids are in bed. Let's go tie one on.

23:25.332 --> 23:27.099
You want me to go to the saloon with you?

23:27.134 --> 23:28.901
That's the idea, yeah.

23:29.168 --> 23:30.536
(SIGHS)

23:32.071 --> 23:34.306
You don't have many
friends, do you, Bohannon?

23:36.375 --> 23:37.476
Hmm.

23:38.711 --> 23:40.011
None living.

23:48.087 --> 23:49.754
(STRAINING)

23:55.127 --> 23:56.928
(MUTTERING)

24:21.453 --> 24:23.120
Brother Phineas?

24:27.798 --> 24:29.465
Hello?

24:32.014 --> 24:33.715
(GROWLING)

24:34.883 --> 24:39.456
Oh! Oh. (SPEAKS NORWEGIAN)

24:42.284 --> 24:44.586
What have you got there? Huh?

24:45.286 --> 24:47.218
- A bone?
- (GROWLS)

24:47.824 --> 24:49.524
(SPEAKS NORWEGIAN)

24:51.627 --> 24:52.760
Oh!

24:53.596 --> 24:54.929
You was hungry!

24:58.455 --> 25:00.268
I want to show you something.

25:03.272 --> 25:06.007
- (PANTS) You see, huh? Yeah?
- (WHIMPERS)

25:06.041 --> 25:09.777
Yeah, I know it's a little scary.
(CHUCKLES)

25:10.211 --> 25:11.612
Yeah.

25:15.751 --> 25:17.284
You know,

25:17.318 --> 25:20.888
I have some bones to bury too, huh.

25:23.424 --> 25:24.758
(EXCLAIMS)

25:29.197 --> 25:30.864
(SNIFFLES)

25:30.898 --> 25:33.233
- (DOG BARKS)
- Yeah, you like it, huh?

25:34.068 --> 25:35.068
Yeah.

25:35.102 --> 25:36.803
(SPEAKS NORWEGIAN)

26:29.355 --> 26:34.539
(POLLY SPEAKING CANTONESE)

26:35.528 --> 26:38.330
My wife gave me this tie. It's easy enough.

26:38.564 --> 26:39.864
(SIGHS)

26:39.898 --> 26:41.299
You don't like the color?

26:41.334 --> 26:43.101
(SPEAKS CANTONESE)

26:43.135 --> 26:44.336
(DOOR OPENS)

26:47.239 --> 26:49.774
Oh, uh... Nevermind. Nevermind.
I'll tie it myself.

26:50.943 --> 26:53.510
- Go on upstairs. Go.
- (HUFFS)

26:59.693 --> 27:00.994
You're dressed for the opera.

27:02.997 --> 27:05.097
I'm taking my housekeeper.

27:05.131 --> 27:07.366
Ah, Polly. I've missed Polly.

27:07.834 --> 27:10.235
You won her on a very lucky hand.

27:10.269 --> 27:13.571
Yeah, she is, uh, a woman of many talents.

27:15.241 --> 27:16.875
- Allow me.
- Hmm?

27:16.909 --> 27:18.276
Allow me.

27:22.781 --> 27:24.782
Mr. Bohannon came to see me today.

27:25.418 --> 27:27.018
One hell of a railroad man.

27:27.486 --> 27:30.087
Yes, it seems he has great
enthusiasm for his work.

27:30.556 --> 27:32.624
As well as the work of others.

27:34.226 --> 27:36.327
He came to me with demands.

27:37.863 --> 27:40.698
Well, Mr. Bohannon is a
stake-holder, Mr. Chang.

27:42.700 --> 27:43.867
Hmm.

27:47.439 --> 27:50.341
This railroad is constructed
on the backs of Chinamen

27:50.375 --> 27:52.910
who work for less than a third
of what you pay white men

27:53.811 --> 27:55.946
and get sick half as often.

27:56.614 --> 27:59.917
These Chinamen are brought
here from the shit-drenched

27:59.951 --> 28:02.953
rice fields of Guangdong
under my authority.

28:03.821 --> 28:07.024
It would be a pity for any
stakeholder to forget that.

28:12.630 --> 28:13.830
Cullen Bohannon is here to stay.

28:13.865 --> 28:16.266
You two will to have to
get used to each other.

28:18.402 --> 28:20.937
Now come here and help
me into my coat, John.

28:24.708 --> 28:25.975
(CHUCKLES)

28:35.552 --> 28:37.219
(SPEAKS CANTONESE)

28:39.022 --> 28:40.189
Polly!

28:43.193 --> 28:45.160
Tell me something, Bohannon.

28:46.429 --> 28:48.663
Why the C.P. for Christ's sake?

28:49.491 --> 28:51.325
My wife left me, Jim.

28:53.262 --> 28:54.896
Son of a bitch.

28:56.131 --> 28:58.232
I thought it was you that done the leaving.

29:00.869 --> 29:02.203
(SCOFFS)

29:02.737 --> 29:03.871
I don't blame her.

29:05.440 --> 29:07.408
I was hoping if I could find her, she...

29:09.611 --> 29:11.378
Guess it don't matter now. (SIGHS)

29:13.383 --> 29:15.117
Trail's so cold it's frostbit.

29:18.121 --> 29:20.023
You got one hell of a brood out here, huh?

29:20.057 --> 29:22.558
Them kids ain't ours, natural.

29:22.592 --> 29:25.561
Strays we picked up along the way.

29:36.239 --> 29:37.639
Gentlemen.

29:41.911 --> 29:43.244
Please, deal me in.

29:54.623 --> 29:56.657
(MUSIC PLAYING)

30:10.706 --> 30:12.206
(INAUDIBLE)

30:18.914 --> 30:20.581
You look surprised to see me, Mr. Bohannon.

30:21.817 --> 30:25.586
(IN MOCK CHINESE ACCENT) Bossee man say
Chief Mandarin can go where he prease.

30:26.888 --> 30:30.524
No. I just thought you Chinese
stayed to yourselves, is all.

30:31.726 --> 30:34.261
Oh, many of my countrymen
are afraid of whites.

30:34.295 --> 30:38.132
Wild and fierce and wicked barbarians,

30:38.166 --> 30:39.666
intent on eating their children.

30:40.135 --> 30:42.269
That's what I tell my kids about you.

30:46.674 --> 30:49.408
There are superstitious fools
among both our peoples.

30:50.077 --> 30:53.613
They attribute our fates to Cai
Shen riding his black tiger,

30:53.648 --> 30:55.882
Jesus Christ on his cross,

30:56.884 --> 30:59.485
Joseph Smith uncovering his tablets,

30:59.520 --> 31:01.320
or to a simple four-leaf clover.

31:01.688 --> 31:04.423
I met a Injun once, prayed
to a bottle of whiskey.

31:04.858 --> 31:07.226
"This is the excellent
foppery of the world,

31:07.261 --> 31:08.927
that when we are sick in fortune

31:08.962 --> 31:10.596
we make guilty of our disasters,

31:10.631 --> 31:12.798
the sun, the moon, the stars,

31:12.832 --> 31:15.501
as if we were villains of necessity."

31:15.935 --> 31:17.870
So. You're a villain.

31:19.372 --> 31:21.606
"I should have been that I am,

31:21.641 --> 31:24.643
had the maidenliest star
in the firmament twinkled

31:25.378 --> 31:26.912
on my bastardizing."

31:29.082 --> 31:31.650
You're pretty well-spoke for
a heathen, ain't you, Chang?

31:55.307 --> 31:57.108
Men like you and I make our own fates,

31:58.276 --> 31:59.877
don't we, Mr. Bohannon?

32:00.445 --> 32:02.213
Our own luck.

32:02.247 --> 32:05.349
It wasn't the stars that brought you
into my rice shop this morning,

32:05.383 --> 32:08.018
or to my pleasure house this afternoon.

32:10.822 --> 32:12.423
It was both railroad business, Mr. Chang.

32:26.303 --> 32:28.471
(GRUNTING)

32:30.208 --> 32:31.407
(YELLS)

32:34.011 --> 32:37.547
(BOTH YELLING IN CANTONESE)

32:58.001 --> 33:00.002
Did the fates give you those cards?

33:01.638 --> 33:03.272
You threw that hand.

33:05.375 --> 33:07.576
It's easy when you're losing
other people's money, isn't it?

33:16.753 --> 33:18.287
(GRUNTING)

33:19.955 --> 33:22.914
_

33:29.665 --> 33:30.865
(GRUNTING)

33:35.404 --> 33:37.371
(GRUNTING)

33:47.783 --> 33:49.850
Do you think it's by luck

33:50.319 --> 33:51.819
that I sit here now?

34:03.198 --> 34:04.731
Leave it alone, Bohannon!

34:10.138 --> 34:11.170
Back up!

35:07.626 --> 35:11.462
(CHUCKLES) You know, the
first time I saw a Chinaman

35:11.496 --> 35:13.497
was in a sideshow tent.

35:14.366 --> 35:16.534
Mr. P.T. Barnum had a whole family of them.

35:16.568 --> 35:18.735
Reading, writing,

35:19.137 --> 35:21.104
eating with their choppy sticks,

35:21.139 --> 35:25.022
dressed in the finest silk.
I felt like Marco Polo.

35:27.304 --> 35:29.408
They have an ancient
civilization, Mr. Bohannon.

35:30.606 --> 35:34.810
They're mysterious and wise, industrious.

35:35.311 --> 35:37.212
Beautiful in their way.

35:37.647 --> 35:40.282
Oh, you can hire them, admire them,

35:41.417 --> 35:44.419
eat their food, lay with their women.

35:46.722 --> 35:48.523
It's easy to get distracted.

35:49.124 --> 35:50.325
Hmm.

35:52.595 --> 35:55.229
Chang's gonna be a problem
for this railroad.

35:55.898 --> 35:57.965
The Union Pacific is
halfway across Wyoming.

35:58.301 --> 36:01.002
Thomas Durant is gobbling
up five miles per day.

36:01.036 --> 36:03.604
With it, government bonds, mineral rights.

36:03.638 --> 36:05.406
At the rate we're going,

36:05.440 --> 36:08.742
we'll have ceded the Weber Canyon
coal fields team before year's end.

36:12.380 --> 36:16.083
Durant is winning the race, Mr. Bohannon.

36:17.619 --> 36:20.187
That is a problem for this railroad.

36:20.822 --> 36:23.524
Durant's resourceful but reckless.

36:24.058 --> 36:26.460
He'll bring the entire U.P.
enterprise down on his head

36:26.494 --> 36:27.861
without somebody there to stop him.

36:28.296 --> 36:29.763
Without you?

36:33.167 --> 36:34.901
Do I have your loyalty?

36:44.879 --> 36:47.013
Do I have your loyalty, sir?

36:55.322 --> 36:56.622
I'm here, ain't I?

36:58.492 --> 37:00.192
(SIGHS) Good.

37:03.497 --> 37:04.630
Mr. Bohannon.

37:07.434 --> 37:09.001
No more distractions.

37:41.567 --> 37:42.867
Fong.

37:44.203 --> 37:46.670
- Tao?
- Sick list.

37:52.778 --> 37:54.747
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

38:15.412 --> 38:16.871
(GRUNTS) Samuel.

38:18.769 --> 38:21.238
- Lock up if you leave.
- Sir.

39:11.488 --> 39:12.754
(SIGHS)

39:14.156 --> 39:15.691
Damn turncoat.

39:17.355 --> 39:20.124
(SIGHS) Never trust a rebel.

39:39.381 --> 39:41.181
Your favorite brand.

39:48.490 --> 39:50.525
Don't get you out of the fare.

39:50.559 --> 39:51.959
(CHUCKLES)

40:02.303 --> 40:03.504
Yah!

40:12.146 --> 40:13.379
(SIGHS)

40:16.918 --> 40:18.752
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

40:19.921 --> 40:21.154
(SIGHS)

40:21.388 --> 40:24.390
Ain't you get enough of
my money last night, Jim?

40:25.660 --> 40:26.760
I swear.

40:28.295 --> 40:29.595
Mr. Bohannon.

40:30.531 --> 40:32.998
It is a pleasure to see you again.

40:34.834 --> 40:37.636
Yeah. Heard you slipped the noose.

40:37.671 --> 40:40.073
Uh, I arrived in camp

40:40.107 --> 40:43.576
with the rest of the Mormon
workers while you was surveying.

40:43.810 --> 40:47.813
When Mr. Huntington told me you
had joined the Central Pacific,

40:47.847 --> 40:49.481
(CHUCKLES)

40:49.515 --> 40:51.684
I prayed for your safe return.

40:53.653 --> 40:56.221
(STUTTERS) I would like to thank you.

40:56.656 --> 40:58.390
I'd like you to step back from my door.

41:00.226 --> 41:02.594
Yeah, I have stepped back, yeah.

41:04.163 --> 41:07.566
I would like to thank you
for revealing the truth.

41:09.502 --> 41:11.703
I am not Bishop Dutson.

41:11.737 --> 41:14.206
I was never Bishop Dutson. (CHUCKLES)

41:18.543 --> 41:20.111
Didn't bother Brigham Young none, I guess.

41:20.813 --> 41:24.248
The blasphemer who sits in Salt
Lake City is a false prophet.

41:24.783 --> 41:27.619
Heavenly Father has shown me, through you,

41:28.453 --> 41:30.488
that I am the one true prophet.

41:31.189 --> 41:32.456
Prophet?

41:33.791 --> 41:37.094
You got any followers 'sides
that tick-bit mongrel?

41:40.098 --> 41:42.733
I will reveal you, Mr. Bohannon,

41:42.767 --> 41:44.335
as you have revealed me.

41:44.736 --> 41:47.571
For if I was never Bishop Dutson,

41:47.805 --> 41:53.309
you have never been reformed
husband and father.

41:54.812 --> 41:56.246
No, you are the devil.

41:56.981 --> 41:59.883
Sent by divine providence to test me,

41:59.917 --> 42:03.787
to forge me into the lion I must become.

42:05.389 --> 42:09.992
Oh, I look forward to
this next test, devil.

42:16.667 --> 42:18.801
Now you think I'm the devil.

42:19.803 --> 42:22.238
(SCOFFS) That's fine.

42:24.041 --> 42:25.474
Probably take a devil to finish this road.

42:26.176 --> 42:27.476
Mmm-hmm.

42:28.645 --> 42:32.247
And you can call yourself whatever you
like, long as you brought a shovel.

42:33.083 --> 42:35.685
Because this ain't the Mormon
fort, you Swedish son of a bitch.

42:35.719 --> 42:37.086
You work for me.

42:40.190 --> 42:41.523
I got a race to win.

